attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a MIPS-based IoT botnet, likely a variant of the Mirai or Gafgyt/Bashlite families. Key malicious behaviors include: 1) Hardcoded Command and Control (C2) communication with the IP 78.142.18.92 (seen in sub_4080f8 and sub_406aa4). 2) Implementation of multiple DDoS attack vectors, including an HTTP flood module (sub_404598) using the string 'GET / HTTP/1.2' and various TCP/UDP/ICMP flood routines. 3) Automated network scanning logic in sub_4080f8 designed to generate random public IP addresses while explicitly avoiding local and private address ranges. 4) Extensive string obfuscation using a simple XOR-based routine (sub_407ef8) with the key 0x54 ('T'). 5) Use of process manipulation techniques such as daemonization via fork() and process name management via prctl() to maintain persistence and evade simple monitoring.
